  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-rotational-symmetry-of-solids" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Rotational Symmetry of Solids</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Rotation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Determine the axis and order of rotational symmetry in solids
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define an axis of rotational symmetry as a line through a solid about which the solid can be rotated to look identical. Identify that different solids have different numbers of axes and different orders of symmetry. Distinguish between axes through faces, vertices, and edges.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Identify the axes of rotational symmetry in common solids (cube, cuboid, cylinder, cone, sphere, triangular prism, regular tetrahedron). Determine the order of rotational symmetry for each axis. Count the total number of axes for each solid.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Analyse real-world objects for rotational symmetry in 3D. Explain how rotational symmetry relates to structural stability. Identify rotational symmetry in architecture, engineering, and nature.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/rotation/rotational-symmetry-of-solids.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/rotation/step-by-step-guide_rotational-symmetry-of-solids.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Groups
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Materials</title>
                <p>
                    Cuboid models (box), string/stick, modelling clay
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Instructions</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Take a cuboid and push a string through the centre of one face to the opposite face.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Rotate the cuboid around the string — how many times does it look identical in one full turn?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Try other face pairs.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Try diagonals.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p>
            Record your results in the table below:
        </p>
        <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                <cell>Axis Position</cell>
                <cell>Order</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Through centres of top/bottom faces</cell>
                <cell>Order 2 (<m>180°</m>)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Through centres of front/back faces</cell>
                <cell>Order 2 (<m>180°</m>)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Through centres of left/right faces</cell>
                <cell>Order 2 (<m>180°</m>)</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
        <p>
            Total: 3 axes, each order 2.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Discussion Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Why not order 4?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        How is a cuboid different from a cube?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What about a cylinder?
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_lqphup7u">
      <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_6h3d61t1">
          Here is an activity to explore on axis of rotation of a box (cuboid).
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_dsfk8tg7">
          <term>Materials</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ipq20lzh">
          <ul xml:id="auto_8y3zizbj">
            <li xml:id="auto_usw4m37z">
              <p xml:id="auto_cshe7alo">
                A cuboid shaped box
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_s64ot384">
              <p xml:id="auto_5iwii907">
                Three strings
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ay4uq7m4">
              <p xml:id="auto_n37cmeeg">
                Pins, ruler and pencil
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_t6cyjpz6">
          <term>Instructions</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_rz6fe1tt">
          <ul xml:id="auto_qowm7tma">
            <li xml:id="auto_8xd8yexi">
              <p xml:id="auto_lloln3to">
                Measure and note down the cuboid's dimensions (length, width, height).
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_c434ssyo">
              <p xml:id="auto_lejtwfbn">
                Mark the centre of box on each face using a pencil and make holes using pins through the centres. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_kb891g6o">
              <p xml:id="auto_5rv4pmmt">
                Put the strings through the holes such that they appear as shown.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_hf9tdtza">
              <p xml:id="auto_bmqnnh1k">
                Suspend the cuboid and spin it around each of the strings and observe the alignment of the cuboid.
                 Does the box appear to be the same as you rotate?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <image width="50%">
          <latex-image label="axis_of_rotation_activity">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \draw(-3,-1)--(-1,-2)--(3,-1)--(1,0)--cycle;
              \draw(-3,-1)--(-3,-2)--(-1,-3)--(3,-2)--(3,-1);
              \draw(-1,-2)--(-1,-3);

              \draw[blue](0,1)--(0,-1);
              \draw[blue](0,-2.8)--(0,-4);

              \draw[red](-2,-2)--(-4,-2.5);
              \draw[red](2.7,-.8)--(4,-.5);

              \draw[green](-1.7,-.7)--(-3,0);
              \draw[green](1,-2)--(3,-3);

            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>

      </statement>
    </activity>

    <exploration xml:id="exploration-3d-symmetry">
        <title>Rotating a Square Prism</title>
        <p>
            You can explore the rotational symmetry of the square prism from <xref ref="auto_t1sdmwvk"/> by dragging the sliders below.
        </p>
        <interactive xml:id="interactive-3d-symmetry" platform="javascript" width="90%" aspect="1:1" source="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/jsxgraph@1.12.2/distrib/jsxgraphcore.js jsxgraph/3d-symmetry.js https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/jsxgraph@1.12.2/distrib/jsxgraph.css">
            <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-3d-symmetry" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1"/>
            <instructions xml:id="inst-3d-symmetry">
                <p>
                    Drag the sliders to rotate the square prism about each axis of symmetry. Can you find all the rotational symmetries?
                </p>
                <p>
                    Press the <c>Reset</c> button if you want to reset the sliders to the default position.
                </p>
            </instructions>
        </interactive>
    </exploration>

    <p xml:id="auto_3fknbqlh">
      <term>Key Takeaway</term>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_1mhwes0z">
      <ul xml:id="auto_och08j6p">
        <li xml:id="auto_w778kvea">
          <p xml:id="auto_q9spdrm2">
            A solid has rotational symmetry if it can be rotated about a fixed straight line and still appears to be the same.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="auto_hfnqgpm4">
          <p xml:id="auto_vewjrsyq">
            The straight line around which the object is rotated is called <term>axis of rotation.</term>
             In the activity, the strings represents the axes of rotational symmetry for the cuboid.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Direct Instruction</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p>
            An <term>axis of rotational symmetry</term> is an imaginary line through a solid around which it can be rotated to look identical.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Key Solids:</alert>
        </p>
        <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                <cell>Solid</cell>
                <cell>Axis Type</cell>
                <cell>Number of Axes</cell>
                <cell>Order</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Cube</cell>
                <cell>Face-to-face</cell>
                <cell>3</cell>
                <cell>4</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Cube</cell>
                <cell>Vertex-to-vertex</cell>
                <cell>4</cell>
                <cell>3</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Cube</cell>
                <cell>Edge-to-edge</cell>
                <cell>6</cell>
                <cell>2</cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
                <cell>Cube</cell>
                <cell><alert>Total</alert></cell>
                <cell><alert>13</alert></cell>
                <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
                <cell>Cuboid</cell>
                <cell>Face-to-face</cell>
                <cell>3</cell>
                <cell>2 (each)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Cylinder</cell>
                <cell>Vertical</cell>
                <cell>1</cell>
                <cell>Infinite</cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
                <cell>Cylinder</cell>
                <cell>Horizontal</cell>
                <cell>Infinite</cell>
                <cell>2 (each)</cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
                <cell>Cone</cell>
                <cell>Vertical (apex to centre of base)</cell>
                <cell>1</cell>
                <cell>Infinite</cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
                <cell>Sphere</cell>
                <cell>Any line through centre</cell>
                <cell>Infinite</cell>
                <cell>Infinite</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Regular tetrahedron</cell>
                <cell>Vertex-to-face</cell>
                <cell>4</cell>
                <cell>3</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Regular tetrahedron</cell>
                <cell>Edge-to-edge</cell>
                <cell>3</cell>
                <cell>2</cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
                <cell>Regular tetrahedron</cell>
                <cell><alert>Total</alert></cell>
                <cell><alert>7</alert></cell>
                <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Regular triangular prism</cell>
                <cell>Through centres of triangular faces</cell>
                <cell>1</cell>
                <cell>3</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Regular triangular prism</cell>
                <cell>Through midpoints of rectangular faces</cell>
                <cell>3</cell>
                <cell>2 (each)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Regular triangular prism</cell>
                <cell><alert>Total</alert></cell>
                <cell><alert>4</alert></cell>
                <cell></cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
        <p>
            <alert>Note:</alert> The triangular prism has 4 axes only if it is a <em>regular</em> triangular prism.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Common Misconception:</alert> Not every line through the centre is an axis of symmetry.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Worked Examples</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p>
            <alert>Problem 1: Cone</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Identify the axes of rotational symmetry of a cone.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        1 axis (vertical, through apex to centre of base).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Order = infinite (any angle of rotation).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Real world: ice cream cone, traffic cone, party hat.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Problem 2: Triangular Prism (Regular)</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Identify the axes of rotational symmetry of a regular triangular prism.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        1 axis through centres of triangular faces (order 3).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        3 axes through midpoints of rectangular faces and opposite edges (order 2 each).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Total = 4 axes.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Problem 3: Cylinder</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Identify the axes of rotational symmetry of a cylinder.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        1 vertical axis (infinite order).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Infinite horizontal axes through centre (each order 2).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Real world: tin can, pipe, pillar.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        How is it different from a cone? A cylinder has horizontal axes; a cone does not.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_t26mtchq">
      <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_te5yo931">
          Find the axes of rotation for a triangular pyramid whose cross-section is an equilateral triangle.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
      <p xml:id="auto_uqp1yy7v">
        The figure below shows a triangular prism whose cross-section is an equialteral triangle.
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_rryix7vj">
        The axis of rotation passes through the traingular face. Therefore, the order of rotation through this axis is <m>3.</m>
      </p>
      <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="triangular_prism_1_axis_of_rotation">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            
            
            % Define vertices of the upright triangular prism
            \coordinate (A) at (0,0,0);  % Bottom front vertex
            \coordinate (B) at (3,0,0);  % Bottom back vertex
            \coordinate (C) at (1.5,3,0); % Top vertex
            \coordinate (A') at (0,0,-3); % Bottom front (back face)
            \coordinate (B') at (3,0,-3); % Bottom back (back face)
            \coordinate (C') at (1.5,3,-3); % Top (back face)

            % Draw edges of the front triangle
            \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
            
            % Draw edges of the back triangle
            \draw[thick] (A') -- (B') -- (C') -- cycle;

            % Connect corresponding vertices of the front and back triangles
            \draw[thick] (A) -- (A');
            \draw[thick] (B) -- (B');
            \draw[thick] (C) -- (C');

            % Axis of rotation through the triangular cross-section
            \draw[dashed,thick] (1.5,1.5,-3.5) -- (1.5,1.5,1)
            node[above] {Axis of Rotation};

            % Shade one side
            \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.5] (A) -- (B) -- (B') -- (A') -- cycle; % Side face shading
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p xml:id="auto_lacepp9r">
        The prism also has other <m>3</m> axes of rotation  with each axis having <m>2</m> orders of rotational symmetry as shown in the figure below:
      </p>

      <image width="70%">
        <latex-image label="triangular_prism_2_axis_of_rotation">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[thick,black](-5,3)--(-6,0)--(-3,0)--cycle;
            \draw[thick,black](-5,3)--(-2,4)--(0,2)--(-3,0)--cycle;
            \draw[style=dashed,thick,gray](-6,0)--(-2.32,2.25);
            \draw[style=dashed,thick,gray](-2.32,2.25)--(0,2);
            \draw[style=dashed,thick,gray](-2.32,2.25)--(-2,4);
            \draw(-4,4)--(-3.6,3.5);
            \draw(-1,0)--(-1.9,0.9) node[right]{Axis of Rotation};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="auto_bfthdtv3">
      <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_4njaxuau">
          Find the axis of rotation of a cone. What is the order of rotational symmetry?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p xml:id="auto_4yzjau9m">
           A cone has one axis of rotation with infinite numbers of order of rotational symmetry since its base is circular.
        </p>
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="cone_axis_of_rotation">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
           

            % Draw the slant edges of the cone
            \draw[thick] (0,4) -- (-2,0); % Left slant edge
            \draw[thick] (0,4) -- (2,0);  % Right slant edge

            \draw[very thick](-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 1);
            \draw[dashed,very thick](-1.95,0) arc (180:0:1.95 and .95);

            % Draw the axis of rotation
            \draw[dashed,black,thick] (0,0) -- (0,5)
              node[above] {Axis of Rotation};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-determinig-order-of-rotational-symmetry-of-polygons">
        <stack label="stk-determinig-order-of-rotational-symmetry-of-polygons" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-3-Rotation/2-3-3-Rotational-Symmetry/Determinig-Order-of-Rotational-Symmetry-of-polygons.xml"/>
    </exercise>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Exit Ticket / Assessment</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        How many axes of rotational symmetry does a cube have? <m>\rightarrow</m> 13.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What is the order of rotational symmetry of a cone about its vertical axis? <m>\rightarrow</m> Infinite.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        A cuboid has how many axes? What order? <m>\rightarrow</m> 3 axes, each order 2.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Name a solid with exactly 1 axis of rotational symmetry. <m>\rightarrow</m> Cone.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Why does a sphere have infinite axes of infinite order? <m>\rightarrow</m> Any line through the centre is an axis, and the circular cross-section at every angle means any rotation maps it onto itself.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

      <exercises xml:id="exercises-subsubsec-determining-the-axis-of-rotation-and-order-of-rotational-symmetry-in-solids">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_ci46yj6l">
        <statement>
          <p xml:id="auto_qagyzmz6">
            Find the other  axes of rotation and order of rotational symmetry of the regular tetrehedron given one of the axes from
             <m>A</m> and passing at the center of the face <m>BDC.</m>.
          </p>
          <image width="70%">
          <latex-image label="regular_tetrahedron_axis_of_rotation">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              % Define vertices of the tetrahedron
              \coordinate (A) at (0,2); 
              \coordinate (B) at (-2,0);
              \coordinate (C) at (2,0);
              \coordinate (D) at (0,1); 

              % Draw edges of the tetrahedron
              \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle; % Base triangle
              \draw[style=dashed,thick] (A) -- (D);
              \draw[style=dashed,thick] (B) -- (D);
              \draw[style=dashed,thick] (C) -- (D);

              % Draw the axis of rotation
              % The axis goes through one vertex (D) and the centroid of the opposite face (triangle ABC)
              \coordinate (Centroid) at (0,.4); % Centroid of the base triangle
              \draw[dashed,purple,thick] (0,.4) -- (0,2.5);
              \draw[purple,thick](0,0)--(0,-.4);

              % Label the axis of rotation
              \node[below,font=\sffamily] at (0,-.4) {Axis of rotation};

              %Label the vertices
              \node[above] at (A) {A};
              \node[below left] at (B) {B};
              \node[right] at (C) {C};
              \node[below] at (D) {D};

              % Shade one side
              \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.5] (B) -- (D) -- (C) -- cycle; % Side face shading

              \fill[red!30,opacity=0.5] (A) -- (B) -- (D) -- cycle; % Side face shading

              \fill[brown!30,opacity=0.5] (A) -- (D) -- (C) -- cycle; % Side face shading
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        </statement>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_wsdln56b">
          <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_dgmtphw3"> 
              Find the axes of rotation and order of rotational symmetry of a triangular base pyramid whose base is:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_co0vbaan">
              <ul xml:id="auto_3n4p5xfn">
                <li xml:id="auto_xpwlh6b2">
                  <p xml:id="auto_10nqfuip">
                    Scalene triangle
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5btebxhv">
                  <p xml:id="auto_awuphnwb">
                    Isosceles triangle
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide physical models (boxes, cans, cones) and string/stick to physically test axes. Start with cylinder and cone (simplest). Use an axis identification checklist. Pair with a mentor.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Complete all solids including tetrahedron. Count all axes for each solid. Compare cube vs cuboid systematically.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extension Learning Experience:</alert> Prove the cube has exactly 13 axes using face/vertex/edge analysis. Investigate Platonic solids symmetry (octahedron, dodecahedron, icosahedron). Research crystal symmetry in chemistry.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
        <p>
            <alert>Extension Activities:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Regular Octahedron:</alert> Investigate the regular octahedron (8 equilateral triangular faces). It has the same symmetry group as a cube. Axes: 3 vertex-to-vertex (order 4), 4 face-to-face (order 3), 6 edge-to-edge (order 2). Total: 13 axes.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Crystal Symmetry:</alert> Research how crystal structure in minerals relates to rotational symmetry. Example: diamond has cubic symmetry.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Platonic Solids:</alert> Build models of all 5 Platonic solids and catalogue their axes of symmetry: Tetrahedron (7), Cube (13), Octahedron (13), Dodecahedron (31), Icosahedron (31).
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>
